Let's call the dimension of the length and width of the base $x$ (they
are the same since it is a \textbf{square} base. Let's call the height
of the box $y$. We want to find the dimensions of a box (x and y) that
minimizes the \textbf{cost} of building it but such that it has a
prescribed volume (16m$^3$). The volume requirement is known as our
\textbf{constraint} and it allows us to find a relationship between our
two variables so that we have only one independent variable. The volume
is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}V=x^2y=16
\end{align*}

and so we conclude that

\begin{align*}
y=\frac{16}{x^2}.
\end{align*}

We now need to consider the cost. The total cost will be the sum of
building the 4 sides ($C_S$), the base ($C_B$), and the top ($C_T$),

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}C=4C_S+C_B+C_T.
\end{align*}

We have that the cost per square metre of the sides is
\textbackslash{}\$20 but for now let's call this number $m$. We then
have that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}C_S=mA_S
\end{align*}

where $A_S$ is the area of the sides. We know the top costs half as much
per square metre and so,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}C_T=\frac{m}{2}A_T.
\end{align*}

Similarly the base costs twice as much per square metre,

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}C_B=2mA_B.
\end{align*}

where $A_B$ and $A_T$ are the base and top areas respectively. In order
to continue, we need to write each surface area in terms of our
independent variable $x$. The surface area of both the base and the top
is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}A_B=A_T=x^2.
\end{align*}

The surface area of each of the sides is

\begin{align*}
A_S=xy=x\frac{16}{x^2}=\frac{16}{x}
\end{align*}

where we have used our relationship for $y$ in terms of $x$. We can now
write the cost

\begin{align*}
C&=4C_S+C_B+C_T\\
&=4m\frac{16}{x}+2mx^2+\frac{m}{2}x^2\\
&=m\left(\frac{64}{x}+\frac{5}{2}x^2\right).
\end{align*}

We seek to find critical points of this function and therefore we take
its derivative and set it to zero,

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}C}{\textrm{d}x}=m\left(-\frac{64}{x^2}+5x\right)=0
\end{align*}

and we see that the only critical point is

\begin{align*}
x^3=\frac{64}{5}.
\end{align*}

Before continuing, it is worth noting that the cost per square metre of
the sides (m=\textbackslash{}\$20) was irrelevant information. In order
to test if our critical point is indeed a minimum we will use the second
derivative test (since there is no closed interval we cannot test the
endpoints). The second derivative is,

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}^2C}{\textrm{d}x^2}=m\left(\frac{128}{x^3}+5\right).
\end{align*}

If we sub in our critical point,

\begin{align*}
\frac{\textrm{d}^2C}{\textrm{d}x^2}=m\left(128\frac{5}{64}+5\right)=m(10+5)=15m=300
\end{align*}

where here we have used the fact that m=20. Since the second derivative
is positive, the objective function, $C$ is concave up and thus we have
a minimum at our critical point. Therefore the dimensions that minimize
the cost of producing the box with volume 16m$^3$ is

\begin{align*}
x=\left(\frac{64}{5}\right)^{1/3} \quad y = \frac{16}{x^2} = 5^{2/3}.
\end{align*}
